# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: depth-estimation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The scientific discipline of computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, multi-dimensional data from a 3D scanner, 3D point clouds from LiDaR sensors, or medical scanning devices.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The technological discipline of computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models to the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Subdisciplines of computer vision include scene reconstruction, object detection, event detection, activity recognition, video tracking, object recognition, 3D pose estimation, learning, indexing, motion estimation, visual servoing, 3D scene modeling, and image restoration.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Computer vision is an interdisciplinary field that deals with how computers can be made to gain high-level understanding from digital images or videos.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] From the perspective of engineering, it seeks to automate tasks that the human visual system can do.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] "Computer vision is concerned with the automatic extraction, analysis, and understanding of useful information from a single image or a sequence of images.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] It involves the development of a theoretical and algorithmic basis to achieve automatic visual understanding." As a scientific discipline, computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, or multi-dimensional data from a medical scanner.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] As a technological discipline, computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models for the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Machine vision refers to a systems engineering discipline, especially in the context of factory automation.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] In more recent times, the terms computer vision and machine vision have converged to a greater degree.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] In the late 1960s, computer vision began at universities that were pioneering artificial intelligence.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] It was meant to mimic the human visual system as a stepping stone to endowing robots with intelligent behavior.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] In 1966, it was believed that this could be achieved through an undergraduate summer project, by attaching a camera to a computer and having it "describe what it saw".
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] What distinguished computer vision from the prevalent field of digital image processing at that time was a desire to extract three-dimensional structure from images with the goal of achieving full scene understanding.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The next decade saw studies based on more rigorous mathematical analysis and quantitative aspects of computer vision.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] These include the concept of scale-space, the inference of shape from various cues such as shading, texture and focus, and contour models known as snakes.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Researchers also realized that many of these mathematical concepts could be treated within the same optimization framework as regularization and Markov random fields.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] By the 1990s, some of the previous research topics became more active than others.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Research in projective 3-D reconstructions led to better understanding of camera calibration.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] With the advent of optimization methods for camera calibration, it was realized that a lot of the ideas were already explored in bundle adjustment theory from the field of photogrammetry.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] This led to methods for sparse 3-D reconstructions of scenes from multiple images.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Progress was made on the dense stereo correspondence problem and further multi-view stereo techniques.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] At the same time, variations of graph cut were used to solve image segmentation.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] This decade also marked the first time statistical learning techniques were used in practice to recognize faces in images (see Eigenface).
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Toward the end of the 1990s, a significant change came about with the increased interaction between the fields of computer graphics and computer vision.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] This included image-based rendering, image morphing, view interpolation, panoramic image stitching and early light-field rendering.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Recent work has seen the resurgence of feature-based methods used in conjunction with machine learning techniques and complex optimization frameworks.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The advancement of Deep Learning techniques has brought further life to the field of computer vision.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The accuracy of deep learning algorithms on several benchmark computer vision data sets for tasks ranging from classification, segmentation and optical flow has surpassed prior methods.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Solid-state physics is another field that is closely related to computer vision.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems rely on image sensors, which detect electromagnetic radiation, which is typically in the form of either visible, infrared or ultraviolet light.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The sensors are designed using quantum physics.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The process by which light interacts with surfaces is explained using physics.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Physics explains the behavior of optics which are a core part of most imaging systems.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Sophisticated image sensors even require quantum mechanics to provide a complete understanding of the image formation process.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Also, various measurement problems in physics can be addressed using computer vision, for example, motion in fluids.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring-textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Neurobiology has greatly influenced the development of computer vision algorithms.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Over the last century, there has been an extensive study of eyes, neurons, and brain structures devoted to the processing of visual stimuli in both humans and various animals.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] This has led to a coarse yet convoluted description of how natural vision systems operate in order to solve certain vision-related tasks.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] These results have led to a sub-field within computer vision where artificial systems are designed to mimic the processing and behavior of biological systems at different levels of complexity.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Also, some of the learning-based methods developed within computer vision (*e.g.* neural net and deep learning based image and feature analysis and classification) have their background in neurobiology.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The Neocognitron, a neural network developed in the 1970s by Kunihiko Fukushima, is an early example of computer vision taking direct inspiration from neurobiology, specifically the primary visual cortex.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Some strands of computer vision research are closely related to the study of biological vision—indeed, just as many strands of AI research are closely tied with research into human intelligence and the use of stored knowledge to interpret, integrate, and utilize visual information.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The field of biological vision studies and models the physiological processes behind visual perception in humans and other animals.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Computer vision, on the other hand, develops and describes the algorithms implemented in software and hardware behind artificial vision systems.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] An interdisciplinary exchange between biological and computer vision has proven fruitful for both fields.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Yet another field related to computer vision is signal processing.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Many methods for processing one-variable signals, typically temporal signals, can be extended in a natural way to the processing of two-variable signals or multi-variable signals in computer vision.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] However, because of the specific nature of images, there are many methods developed within computer vision that have no counterpart in the processing of one-variable signals.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Together with the multi-dimensionality of the signal, this defines a subfield in signal processing as a part of computer vision.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Robot navigation sometimes deals with autonomous path planning or deliberation for robotic systems to navigate through an environment.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] A detailed understanding of these environments is required to navigate through them.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Visual computing is a generic term for all computer science disciplines dealing with images and 3D models, such as computer graphics, image processing, visualization, computer vision, virtual and augmented reality, video processing, and computational visualistics.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes aspects of pattern recognition, human computer interaction, machine learning and digital libraries.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The core challenges are the acquisition, processing, analysis and rendering of visual information (mainly images and video).
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Application areas include industrial quality control, medical image processing and visualization, surveying, robotics, multimedia systems, virtual heritage, special effects in movies and television, and ludology.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes digital art and digital media studies.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Besides the above-mentioned views on computer vision, many of the related research topics can also be studied from a purely mathematical point of view.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] For example, many methods in computer vision are based on statistics, optimization or geometry.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Finally, a significant part of the field is devoted to the implementation aspect of computer vision; how existing methods can be realized in various combinations of software and hardware, or how these methods can be modified in order to gain processing speed without losing too much performance.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Computer vision is also used in fashion eCommerce, inventory management, patent search, furniture, and the beauty industry.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The fields most closely related to computer vision are image processing, image analysis and machine vision.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] There is a significant overlap in the range of techniques and applications that these cover.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] This implies that the basic techniques that are used and developed in these fields are similar, something which can be interpreted as there is only one field with different names.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] In image processing, the input and output are both images, whereas in computer vision, the input is an image or video, and the output could be an enhanced image, an analysis of the image's content, or even a system's behavior based on that analysis.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Computer graphics produces image data from 3D models, and computer vision often produces 3D models from image data.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] There is also a trend towards a combination of the two disciplines, *e.g.*, as explored in augmented reality.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Photogrammetry also overlaps with computer vision, e.g., stereophotogrammetry vs. computer stereo vision.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Applications range from tasks such as industrial machine vision systems which, say, inspect bottles speeding by on a production line, to research into artificial intelligence and computers or robots that can comprehend the world around them.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The computer vision and machine vision fields have significant overlap.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Computer vision covers the core technology of automated image analysis which is used in many fields.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Machine vision usually refers to a process of combining automated image analysis with other methods and technologies to provide automated inspection and robot guidance in industrial applications.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] In many computer-vision applications, computers are pre-programmed to solve a particular task, but methods based on learning are now becoming increasingly common.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] For 2024, the leading areas of computer vision were industry (market size US$5.22 billion), medicine (market size US$2.6 billion), military (market size US$996.2 million).
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] One of the most prominent application fields is medical computer vision, or medical image processing, characterized by the extraction of information from image data to diagnose a patient.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] An example of this is the detection of tumours, arteriosclerosis or other malign changes, and a variety of dental pathologies; measurements of organ dimensions, blood flow, etc. are another example.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] It also supports medical research by providing new information: *e.g.*, about the structure of the brain or the quality of medical treatments.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Applications of computer vision in the medical area also include enhancement of images interpreted by humans—ultrasonic images or X-ray images, for example—to reduce the influence of noise.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] A second application area in computer vision is in industry, sometimes called machine vision, where information is extracted for the purpose of supporting a production process.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] One example is quality control where details or final products are being automatically inspected in order to find defects.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] One of the most prevalent fields for such inspecti is the Wafer industry in which every single Wafer is being measured and inspected for inaccuracies or defects to prevent a computer chip from coming to market in an unusable manner.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Another example is a measurement of the position and orientation of details to be picked up by a robot arm.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Machine vision is also heavily used in the agricultural processes to remove undesirable foodstuff from bulk material, a process called optical sorting.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The obvious examples are the detection of enemy soldiers or vehicles and missile guidance.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] More advanced systems for missile guidance send the missile to an area rather than a specific target, and target selection is made when the missile reaches the area based on locally acquired image data.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Modern military concepts, such as "battlefield awareness", imply that various sensors, including image sensors, provide a rich set of information about a combat scene that can be used to support strategic decisions.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] In this case, automatic processing of the data is used to reduce complexity and to fuse information from multiple sensors to increase reliability.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] One of the newer application areas is autonomous vehicles, which include submersibles, land-based vehicles (small robots with wheels, cars, or trucks), aerial vehicles, and unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV).
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The level of autonomy ranges from fully autonomous (unmanned) vehicles to vehicles where computer-vision-based systems support a driver or a pilot in various situations.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Fully autonomous vehicles typically use computer vision for navigation, e.g., for knowing where they are or mapping their environment (SLAM), for detecting obstacles.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] It can also be used for detecting certain task-specific events, *e.g.*, a UAV looking for forest fires.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Examples of supporting systems are obstacle warning systems in cars, cameras and LiDAR sensors in vehicles, and systems for autonomous landing of aircraft.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Several car manufacturers have demonstrated systems for autonomous driving of cars.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] There are ample examples of military autonomous vehicles ranging from advanced missiles to UAVs for recon missions or missile guidance.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Space exploration is already being made with autonomous vehicles using computer vision, *e.g.*, NASA's *Curiosity* and CNSA's *Yutu-2* rover.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Materials such as rubber and silicon are being used to create sensors that allow for applications such as detecting microundulations and calibrating robotic hands.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Rubber can be used in order to create a mold that can be placed over a finger, inside of this mold would be multiple strain gauges.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The finger mold and sensors could then be placed on top of a small sheet of rubber containing an array of rubber pins.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] A user can then wear the finger mold and trace a surface.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] A computer can then read the data from the strain gauges and measure if one or more of the pins are being pushed upward.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] If a pin is being pushed upward then the computer can recognize this as an imperfection in the surface.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] This sort of technology is useful in order to receive accurate data on imperfections on a very large surface.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Another variation of this finger mold sensor are sensors that contain a camera suspended in silicon.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The silicon forms a dome around the outside of the camera and embedded in the silicon are point markers that are equally spaced.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] These cameras can then be placed on devices such as robotic hands in order to allow the computer to receive highly accurate tactile data.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Each of the application areas described above employ a range of computer vision tasks; more or less well-defined measurement problems or processing problems, which can be solved using a variety of methods.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Some examples of typical computer vision tasks are presented below.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Computer vision tasks include methods for acquiring, processing, analyzing and understanding digital images, and extraction of high-dimensional data from the real world in order to produce numerical or symbolic information, *e.g.*, in the forms of decisions.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Understanding in this context means the transformation of visual images into descriptions of the world that can interface with other thought processes and elicit appropriate action.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] This image understanding can be seen as the disentangling of symbolic information from image data using models constructed with the aid of geometry, physics, statistics, and learning theory.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The classical problem in computer vision, image processing, and machine vision is that of determining whether or not the image data contains some specific object, feature, or activity.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Different varieties of recognition problem are described in the literature.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Currently, the best algorithms for such tasks are based on convolutional neural networks.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] An illustration of their capabilities is given by the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge; this is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and 1000 object classes used in the competition.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests is now close to that of humans.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on the stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters (an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras).
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained classes, such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this with ease.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Several tasks relate to motion estimation, where an image sequence is processed to produce an estimate of the velocity either at each points in the image or in the 3D scene or even of the camera that produces the images.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Given one or (typically) more images of a scene, or a video, scene reconstruction aims at computing a 3D model of the scene.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] In the simplest case, the model can be a set of 3D points.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods produce a complete 3D surface model.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The advent of 3D imaging not requiring motion or scanning, and related processing algorithms is enabling rapid advances in this field.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Grid-based 3D sensing can be used to acquire 3D images from multiple angles.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Algorithms are now available to stitch multiple 3D images together into point clouds and 3D models.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Image restoration comes into the picture when the original image is degraded or damaged due to some external factors like lens wrong positioning, transmission interference, low lighting or motion blurs, etc., which is referred to as noise.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] When the images are degraded or damaged, the information to be extracted from them also gets damaged.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Therefore, we need to recover or restore the image as it was intended to be.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The aim of image restoration is the removal of noise (sensor noise, motion blur, etc.) from images.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The simplest possible approach for noise removal is various types of filters, such as low-pass filters or median filters.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods assume a model of how the local image structures look to distinguish them from noise.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] By first analyzing the image data in terms of the local image structures, such as lines or edges, and then controlling the filtering based on local information from the analysis step, a better level of noise removal is usually obtained compared to the simpler approaches.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The organization of a computer vision system is highly application-dependent.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Some systems are stand-alone applications that solve a specific measurement or detection problem, while others constitute a sub-system of a larger design which, for example, also contains sub-systems for control of mechanical actuators, planning, information databases, man-machine interfaces, etc.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The specific implementation of a computer vision system also depends on whether its functionality is pre-specified or if some part of it can be learned or modified during operation.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Many functions are unique to the application.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] There are, however, typical functions that are found in many computer vision systems.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] More complex features may be related to texture, shape, or motion.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Image-understanding systems (IUS) include three levels of abstraction as follows: low level includes image primitives such as edges, texture elements, or regions; intermediate level includes boundaries, surfaces and volumes; and high level includes objects, scenes, or events.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Many of these requirements are entirely topics for further research.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] The representational requirements in the designing of IUS for these levels are: representation of prototypical concepts, concept organization, spatial knowledge, temporal knowledge, scaling, and description by comparison and differentiation.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] While inference refers to the process of deriving new, not explicitly represented facts from currently known facts, control refers to the process that selects which of the many inference, search, and matching techniques should be applied at a particular stage of processing.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Inference and control requirements for IUS are: search and hypothesis activation, matching and hypothesis testing, generation and use of expectations, change and focus of attention, certainty and strength of belief, inference and goal satisfaction.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] There are many kinds of computer vision systems; however, all of them contain these basic elements: a power source, at least one image acquisition device (camera, ccd, etc.), a processor, and control and communication cables or some kind of wireless interconnection mechanism.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] In addition, a practical vision system contains software, as well as a display in order to monitor the system.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Vision systems for inner spaces, as most industrial ones, contain an illumination system and may be placed in a controlled environment.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Furthermore, a completed system includes many accessories, such as camera supports, cables, and connectors.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems use visible-light cameras passively viewing a scene at frame rates of at most 60 frames per second (usually far slower).
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Such hardware captures "images" that are then processed often using the same computer vision algorithms used to process visible-light images.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] For applications in robotics, fast, real-time video systems are critically important and often can simplify the processing needed for certain algorithms.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] When combined with a high-speed projector, fast image acquisition allows 3D measurement and feature tracking to be realized.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] Egocentric vision systems are composed of a wearable camera that automatically take pictures from a first-person perspective.
[src:depth-estimation/computer-vision] As of 2016, vision processing units are emerging as a new class of processors to complement CPUs and graphics processing units (GPUs) in this role.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A **convolutional neural network** (**CNN**) is a type of feedforward neural network that learns features via filter (or kernel) optimization.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This type of deep learning network has been applied to process and make predictions from many different types of data including text, images and audio.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are the de-facto standard in deep learning-based approaches to computer vision and image processing, and have only recently been replaced—in some cases—by newer architectures such as the transformer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Vanishing gradients and exploding gradients, seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks, are prevented by the regularization that comes from using shared weights over fewer connections.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, for *each* neuron in the fully-connected layer, 10,000 weights would be required for processing an image sized 100 × 100 pixels.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, applying cascaded *convolution* (or cross-correlation) kernels, only 25 weights for each convolutional layer are required to process 5x5-sized tiles.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Higher-layer features are extracted from wider context windows, compared to lower-layer features.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are also known as **shift invariant** or **space invariant artificial neural networks**, based on the shared-weight architecture of the convolution kernels or filters that slide along input features and provide translation-equivariant responses known as feature maps.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Counter-intuitively, most convolutional neural networks are not invariant to translation, due to the downsampling operation they apply to the input.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Feedforward neural networks are usually fully connected networks, that is, each neuron in one layer is connected to all neurons in the next layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "full connectivity" of these networks makes them prone to overfitting data.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks were inspired by biological processes in that the connectivity pattern between neurons resembles the organization of the animal visual cortex.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Individual cortical neurons respond to stimuli only in a restricted region of the visual field known as the receptive field.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The receptive fields of different neurons partially overlap such that they cover the entire visual field.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use relatively little pre-processing compared to other image classification algorithms.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This means that the network learns to optimize the filters (or kernels) through automated learning, whereas in traditional algorithms these filters are hand-engineered.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This simplifies and automates the process, enhancing efficiency and scalability overcoming human-intervention bottlenecks.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A convolutional neural network consists of an input layer, hidden layers and an output layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional neural network, the hidden layers include one or more layers that perform convolutions.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typically this includes a layer that performs a dot product of the convolution kernel with the layer's input matrix.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This product is usually the Frobenius inner product, and its activation function is commonly ReLU.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As the convolution kernel slides along the input matrix for the layer, the convolution operation generates a feature map, which in turn contributes to the input of the next layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is followed by other layers such as pooling layers, fully connected layers, and normalization layers.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Here it should be noted how close a convolutional neural network is to a matched filter.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (number of inputs) × (feature map height) × (feature map width) × (feature map channels).
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional layers convolve the input and pass its result to the next layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to the response of a neuron in the visual cortex to a specific stimulus.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each convolutional neuron processes data only for its receptive field.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although fully connected feedforward neural networks can be used to learn features and classify data, this architecture is generally impractical for larger inputs (e.g., high-resolution images), which would require massive numbers of neurons because each pixel is a relevant input feature.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A fully connected layer for an image of size 100 × 100 has 10,000 weights for *each* neuron in the second layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution reduces the number of free parameters, allowing the network to be deeper.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, using a 5 × 5 tiling region, each with the same shared weights, requires only 25 neurons.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using shared weights means there are many fewer parameters, which helps avoid the vanishing gradients and exploding gradients problems seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To speed processing, standard convolutional layers can be replaced by depthwise separable convolutional layers, which are based on a depthwise convolution followed by a pointwise convolution.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The *depthwise convolution* is a spatial convolution applied independently over each channel of the input tensor, while the *pointwise convolution* is a standard convolution restricted to the use of $1\times 1$ kernels.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks may include local and/or global pooling layers along with traditional convolutional layers.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling layers reduce the dimensions of data by combining the outputs of neuron clusters at one layer into a single neuron in the next layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Local pooling combines small clusters, tiling sizes such as 2 × 2 are commonly used.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Global pooling acts on all the neurons of the feature map.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are two common types of pooling in popular use: max and average.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] *Max pooling* uses the maximum value of each local cluster of neurons in the feature map, while *average pooling* takes the average value.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fully connected layers connect every neuron in one layer to every neuron in another layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the same as a traditional multilayer perceptron neural network (MLP).
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in the fully connected layer receives input from all the neurons in the previous layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These inputs are weighted and summed with the corresponding biases, and then passed through an activation function to perform a nonlinear transformation, generating the output.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The flattened matrix goes through a fully connected layer to classify the images.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In neural networks, each neuron receives input from some number of locations in the previous layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional layer, each neuron receives input from only a restricted area of the previous layer called the neuron's *receptive field*.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Whereas, in a fully connected layer, the receptive field is the *entire previous layer*.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, in each convolutional layer, each neuron takes input from a larger area in the input than previous layers.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is due to applying the convolution over and over, which takes the value of a pixel into account, as well as its surrounding pixels.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When using dilated layers, the number of pixels in the receptive field remains constant, but the field is more sparsely populated as its dimensions grow when combining the effect of several layers.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To manipulate the receptive field size as desired, there are some alternatives to the standard convolutional layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, atrous or dilated convolution expands the receptive field size without increasing the number of parameters by interleaving visible and blind regions.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Moreover, a single dilated convolutional layer can comprise filters with multiple dilation ratios, thus having a variable receptive field size.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in a neural network computes an output value by applying a specific function to the input values received from the receptive field in the previous layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The function that is applied to the input values is determined by a vector of weights and a bias (typically real numbers).
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning consists of iteratively adjusting these biases and weights.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The vectors of weights and biases are called *filters* and represent particular features of the input (e.g., a particular shape).
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A distinguishing feature of CNNs is that many neurons can share the same filter.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces the memory footprint because a single bias and a single vector of weights are used across all receptive fields that share that filter, as opposed to each receptive field having its own bias and vector weighting.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional neural network is essentially the reverse of a CNN.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It consists of deconvolutional layers and unpooling layers.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional layer is the transpose of a convolutional layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Specifically, a convolutional layer can be written as a multiplication with a matrix, and a deconvolutional layer is multiplication with the transpose of that matrix.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The max-unpooling layer is the simplest, as it simply copies each entry multiple times.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a 2-by-2 max-unpooling layer is $[x]\mapsto {\begin{bmatrix}x&x\\x&x\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Deconvolution layers are used in image generators.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By default, it creates periodic checkerboard artifact, which can be fixed by upscale-then-convolve.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNN are often compared to the way the brain achieves vision processing in living organisms.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Work by Hubel and Wiesel in the 1950s and 1960s showed that cat visual cortices contain neurons that individually respond to small regions of the visual field.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Provided the eyes are not moving, the region of visual space within which visual stimuli affect the firing of a single neuron is known as its receptive field.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neighboring cells have similar and overlapping receptive fields.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Receptive field size and location varies systematically across the cortex to form a complete map of visual space.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The cortex in each hemisphere represents the contralateral visual field.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hubel and Wiesel also proposed a cascading model of these two types of cells for use in pattern recognition tasks.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same paper, Fukushima also introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "neocognitron" was introduced by Fukushima in 1980.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Several supervised and unsupervised learning algorithms have been proposed over the decades to train the weights of a neocognitron.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Today, however, the CNN architecture is usually trained through backpropagation.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fukushima's ReLU activation function was not used in his neocognitron since all the weights were nonnegative; lateral inhibition was used instead.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The rectifier has become a very popular activation function for CNNs and deep neural networks in general.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The term "convolution" first appears in neural networks in a paper by Toshiteru Homma, Les Atlas, and Robert Marks II at the first Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems in 1987.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their paper replaced multiplication with convolution in time, inherently providing shift invariance, motivated by and connecting more directly to the signal-processing concept of a filter, and demonstrated it on a speech recognition task.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They also pointed out that as a data-trainable system, convolution is essentially equivalent to correlation since reversal of the weights does not affect the final learned function ("For convenience, we denote * as correlation instead of convolution.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that convolving a(t) with b(t) is equivalent to correlating a(-t) with b(t).").
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Modern CNN implementations typically do correlation and call it convolution, for convenience, as they did here.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel et al. for phoneme recognition and was an early convolutional network exhibiting shift-invariance.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A TDNN is a 1-D convolutional neural net where the convolution is performed along the time axis of the data.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the first CNN utilizing weight sharing in combination with a training by gradient descent, using backpropagation.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, while also using a pyramidal structure as in the neocognitron, it performed a global optimization of the weights instead of a local one.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs are convolutional networks that share weights along the temporal dimension.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They allow speech signals to be processed time-invariantly.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Hampshire and Waibel introduced a variant that performs a two-dimensional convolution.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since these TDNNs operated on spectrograms, the resulting phoneme recognition system was invariant to both time and frequency shifts, as with images processed by a neocognitron.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs improved the performance of far-distance speech recognition.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) designed a 2-D CNN system to recognize hand-written ZIP Code numbers.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the lack of an efficient training method to determine the kernel coefficients of the involved convolutions meant that all the coefficients had to be laboriously hand-designed.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Following the advances in the training of 1-D CNNs by Waibel et al.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) used back-propagation to learn the convolution kernel coefficients directly from images of hand-written numbers.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning was thus fully automatic, performed better than manual coefficient design, and was suited to a broader range of image recognition problems and image types.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1988) used back-propagation to train the convolution kernels of a CNN for alphabets recognition.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was called shift-invariant pattern recognition neural network before the name CNN was coined later in the early 1990s.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Wei Zhang et al. also applied the same CNN without the last fully connected layer for medical image object segmentation (1991) and breast cancer detection in mammograms (1994).
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach became a foundation of modern computer vision.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Yamaguchi et al. introduced the concept of max pooling, a fixed filtering operation that calculates and propagates the maximum value of a given region.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They did so by combining TDNNs with max pooling to realize a speaker-independent isolated word recognition system.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In their system they used several TDNNs per word, one for each syllable.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The results of each TDNN over the input signal were combined using max pooling and the outputs of the pooling layers were then passed on to networks performing the actual word classification.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a variant of the neocognitron called the *cresceptron*, instead of using Fukushima's spatial averaging with inhibition and saturation, J.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weng et al. in 1993 used max pooling, where a downsampling unit computes the maximum of the activations of the units in its patch, introducing this method into the vision field.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is often used in modern CNNs.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] LeNet-5, a pioneering 7-level convolutional network by LeCun et al. in 1995, classifies hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32×32 pixel images.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The ability to process higher-resolution images requires larger and more layers of convolutional neural networks, so this technique is constrained by the availability of computing resources.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was superior than other commercial courtesy amount reading systems (as of 1995).
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The system was integrated in NCR's check reading systems, and fielded in several American banks since June 1996, reading millions of checks per day.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A shift-invariant neural network was proposed by Wei Zhang et al. for image character recognition in 1988.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is a modified Neocognitron by keeping only the convolutional interconnections between the image feature layers and the last fully connected layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was trained with back-propagation.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The training algorithm was further improved in 1991 to improve its generalization ability.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model architecture was modified by removing the last fully connected layer and applied for medical image segmentation (1991) and automatic detection of breast cancer in mammograms (1994).
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A different convolution-based design was proposed in 1988 for application to decomposition of one-dimensional electromyography convolved signals via de-convolution.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This design was modified in 1989 to other de-convolution-based designs.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although CNNs were invented in the 1980s, their breakthrough in the 2000s required fast implementations on graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Jung that standard neural networks can be greatly accelerated on GPUs.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 20 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2005, another paper also emphasised the value of GPGPU for machine learning.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The first GPU-implementation of a CNN was described in 2006 by K.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 4 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same period, GPUs were also used for unsupervised training of deep belief networks.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2010, Dan Ciresan et al. at IDSIA trained deep feedforward networks on GPUs.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, they extended this to CNNs, accelerating by 60 compared to training CPU.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, the network won an image recognition contest where they achieved superhuman performance for the first time.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Then they won more competitions and achieved state of the art on several benchmarks.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Subsequently, AlexNet, a similar GPU-based CNN by Alex Krizhevsky et al. won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was an early catalytic event for the AI boom.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Compared to the training of CNNs using GPUs, not much attention was given to CPU.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (Viebke et al 2019) parallelizes CNN by thread- and SIMD-level parallelism that is available on the Intel Xeon Phi.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the past, traditional multilayer perceptron (MLP) models were used for image recognition.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the full connectivity between nodes caused the curse of dimensionality, and was computationally intractable with higher-resolution images.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A 1000×1000-pixel image with RGB color channels has 3 million weights per fully-connected neuron, which is too high to feasibly process efficiently at scale.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, in CIFAR-10, images are only of size 32×32×3 (32 wide, 32 high, 3 color channels), so a single fully connected neuron in the first hidden layer of a regular neural network would have 32*32*3 = 3,072 weights.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Also, such network architecture does not take into account the spatial structure of data, treating input pixels which are far apart in the same way as pixels that are close together.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This ignores locality of reference in data with a grid-topology (such as images), both computationally and semantically.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, full connectivity of neurons is wasteful for purposes such as image recognition that are dominated by spatially local input patterns.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional neural networks are variants of multilayer perceptrons, designed to emulate the behavior of a visual cortex.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These models mitigate the challenges posed by the MLP architecture by exploiting the strong spatially local correlation present in natural images.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Together, these properties allow CNNs to achieve better generalization on vision problems.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weight sharing dramatically reduces the number of free parameters learned, thus lowering the memory requirements for running the network and allowing the training of larger, more powerful networks.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A CNN architecture is formed by a stack of distinct layers that transform the input volume into an output volume (e.g. holding the class scores) through a differentiable function.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A few distinct types of layers are commonly used.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The convolutional layer is the core building block of a CNN.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The layer's parameters consist of a set of learnable filters (or kernels), which have a small receptive field, but extend through the full depth of the input volume.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] During the forward pass, each filter is convolved across the width and height of the input volume, computing the dot product between the filter entries and the input, producing a 2-dimensional activation map of that filter.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As a result, the network learns filters that activate when it detects some specific type of feature at some spatial position in the input.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Stacking the activation maps for all filters along the depth dimension forms the full output volume of the convolution layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Every entry in the output volume can thus also be interpreted as an output of a neuron that looks at a small region in the input.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each entry in an activation map use the same set of parameters that define the filter.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning has been adapted for use in convolutional layers by using sparse patches with a high-mask ratio and a global response normalization layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When dealing with high-dimensional inputs such as images, it is impractical to connect neurons to all neurons in the previous volume because such a network architecture does not take the spatial structure of the data into account.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks exploit spatially local correlation by enforcing a sparse local connectivity pattern between neurons of adjacent layers: each neuron is connected to only a small region of the input volume.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The extent of this connectivity is a hyperparameter called the receptive field of the neuron.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The connections are local in space (along width and height), but always extend along the entire depth of the input volume.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Such an architecture ensures that the learned filters produce the strongest response to a spatially local input pattern.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The spatial size of the output volume is a function of the input volume size W , the kernel field size K of the convolutional layer neurons, the stride S , and the amount of zero padding P on the border.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] If this number is not an integer, then the strides are incorrect and the neurons cannot be tiled to fit across the input volume in a symmetric way.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In general, setting zero padding to be ${\textstyle P=(K-1)/2}$ when the stride is $S=1$ ensures that the input volume and output volume will have the same size spatially.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, it is not always completely necessary to use all of the neurons of the previous layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a neural network designer may decide to use just a portion of padding.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A parameter sharing scheme is used in convolutional layers to control the number of free parameters.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It relies on the assumption that if a patch feature is useful to compute at some spatial position, then it should also be useful to compute at other positions.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Denoting a single 2-dimensional slice of depth as a *depth slice*, the neurons in each depth slice are constrained to use the same weights and bias.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since all neurons in a single depth slice share the same parameters, the forward pass in each depth slice of the convolutional layer can be computed as a convolution of the neuron's weights with the input volume.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Therefore, it is common to refer to the sets of weights as a filter (or a kernel), which is convolved with the input.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The result of this convolution is an activation map, and the set of activation maps for each different filter are stacked together along the depth dimension to produce the output volume.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Parameter sharing contributes to the translation invariance of the CNN architecture.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sometimes, the parameter sharing assumption may not make sense.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is especially the case when the input images to a CNN have some specific centered structure; for which we expect completely different features to be learned on different spatial locations.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One practical example is when the inputs are faces that have been centered in the image: we might expect different eye-specific or hair-specific features to be learned in different parts of the image.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In that case it is common to relax the parameter sharing scheme, and instead simply call the layer a "locally connected layer".
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In this layer, the convolutional kernels' parameters are not shared.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Instead, the network learns independent weights and biases for each spatial location.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This allows each location to have its own feature-learning ability, making it better suited to handle images with distinct central structures or irregular features.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another important concept of CNNs is pooling, which is used as a form of non-linear down-sampling.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling provides downsampling because it reduces the spatial dimensions (height and width) of the input feature maps while retaining the most important information.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are several non-linear functions to implement pooling, where *max pooling* and *average pooling* are the most common.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling aggregates information from small regions of the input creating partitions of the input feature map, typically using a fixed-size window (like 2x2) and applying a stride (often 2) to move the window across the input.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that without using a stride greater than 1, pooling would not perform downsampling, as it would simply move the pooling window across the input one step at a time, without reducing the size of the feature map.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the stride is what actually causes the downsampling by determining how much the pooling window moves over the input.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Intuitively, the exact location of a feature is less important than its rough location relative to other features.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the idea behind the use of pooling in convolutional neural networks.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer serves to progressively reduce the spatial size of the representation, to reduce the number of parameters, memory footprint and amount of computation in the network, and hence to also control overfitting.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is common to periodically insert a pooling layer between successive convolutional layers (each one typically followed by an activation function, such as a ReLU layer) in a CNN architecture.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] While pooling layers contribute to local translation invariance, they do not provide global translation invariance in a CNN, unless a form of global pooling is used.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer commonly operates independently on every depth, or slice, of the input and resizes it spatially.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The depth dimension remains unchanged (this is true for other forms of pooling as well).
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In addition to max pooling, pooling units can use other functions, such as average pooling or ℓ2-norm pooling.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Average pooling was often used historically but has recently fallen out of favor compared to max pooling, which generally performs better in practice.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to the effects of fast spatial reduction of the size of the representation, there is a recent trend towards using smaller filters or discarding pooling layers altogether.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A channel max pooling (CMP) operation layer conducts the MP operation along the channel side among the corresponding positions of the consecutive feature maps for the purpose of redundant information elimination.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The CMP makes the significant features gather together within fewer channels, which is important for fine-grained image classification that needs more discriminating features.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Meanwhile, another advantage of the CMP operation is to make the channel number of feature maps smaller before it connects to the first fully connected (FC) layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Similar to the MP operation, we denote the input feature maps and output feature maps of a CMP layer as F ∈ R(C×M×N) and C ∈ R(c×M×N), respectively, where C and c are the channel numbers of the input and output feature maps, M and N are the widths and the height of the feature maps, respectively.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that the CMP operation only changes the channel number of the feature maps.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The width and the height of the feature maps are not changed, which is different from the MP operation.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is the abbreviation of rectified linear unit.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was proposed by Alston Householder in 1941, and used in CNN by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1969.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU applies the non-saturating activation function ${\textstyle f(x)=\max(0,x)}$ .
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It effectively removes negative values from an activation map by setting them to zero.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It introduces nonlinearity to the decision function and in the overall network without affecting the receptive fields of the convolution layers.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, Xavier Glorot, Antoine Bordes and Yoshua Bengio found that ReLU enables better training of deeper networks, compared to widely used activation functions prior to 2011.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other functions can also be used to increase nonlinearity, for example the saturating hyperbolic tangent $f(x)=\tanh(x)$ , $f(x)=|\tanh(x)|$ , and the sigmoid function ${\textstyle \sigma (x)=(1+e^{-x})^{-1}}$ .
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is often preferred to other functions because it trains the neural network several times faster without a significant penalty to generalization accuracy.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] After several convolutional and max pooling layers, the final classification is done via fully connected layers.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neurons in a fully connected layer have connections to all activations in the previous layer, as seen in regular (non-convolutional) artificial neural networks.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their activations can thus be computed as an affine transformation, with matrix multiplication followed by a bias offset (vector addition of a learned or fixed bias term).
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "loss layer", or "loss function", exemplifies how training penalizes the deviation between the predicted output of the network, and the true data labels (during supervised learning).
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Various loss functions can be used, depending on the specific task.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The Softmax loss function is used for predicting a single class of *K* mutually exclusive classes.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sigmoid cross-entropy loss is used for predicting *K* independent probability values in $[0,1]$ .
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Euclidean loss is used for regressing to real-valued labels $(-\infty ,\infty )$ .
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hyperparameters are various settings that are used to control the learning process.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use more hyperparameters than a standard multilayer perceptron (MLP).
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Padding is the addition of (typically) 0-valued pixels on the borders of an image.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is done so that the border pixels are not undervalued (lost) from the output because they would ordinarily participate in only a single receptive field instance.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The padding applied is typically one less than the corresponding kernel dimension.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a convolutional layer using 3x3 kernels would receive a 2-pixel pad, that is 1 pixel on each side of the image.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The stride is the number of pixels that the analysis window moves on each iteration.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A stride of 2 means that each kernel is offset by 2 pixels from its predecessor.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since feature map size decreases with depth, layers near the input layer tend to have fewer filters while higher layers can have more.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To equalize computation at each layer, the product of feature values *va* with pixel position is kept roughly constant across layers.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Preserving more information about the input would require keeping the total number of activations (number of feature maps times number of pixel positions) non-decreasing from one layer to the next.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The number of feature maps directly controls the capacity and depends on the number of available examples and task complexity.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Common filter sizes found in the literature vary greatly, and are usually chosen based on the data set.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typical filter sizes range from 1x1 to 7x7.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As two famous examples, AlexNet used 3x3, 5x5, and 11x11.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The challenge is to find the right level of granularity so as to create abstractions at the proper scale, given a particular data set, and without overfitting.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is typically used, often with a 2x2 dimension.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This implies that the input is drastically downsampled, reducing processing cost.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Greater pooling reduces the dimension of the signal, and may result in unacceptable information loss.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Often, non-overlapping pooling windows perform best.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Dilation involves ignoring pixels within a kernel.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces processing memory potentially without significant signal loss.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A dilation of 2 on a 3x3 kernel expands the kernel to 5x5, while still processing 9 (evenly spaced) pixels.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Accordingly, dilation of 4 expands the kernel to 7x7.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is commonly assumed that CNNs are invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution or pooling layers within a CNN that do not have a stride greater than one are indeed equivariant to translations of the input.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Furthermore, if a CNN makes use of fully connected layers, translation equivariance does not imply translation invariance, as the fully connected layers are not invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One solution for complete translation invariance is avoiding any down-sampling throughout the network and applying global average pooling at the last layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Additionally, several other partial solutions have been proposed, such as anti-aliasing before downsampling operations, spatial transformer networks, data augmentation, subsampling combined with pooling, and capsule neural networks.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The accuracy of the final model is typically estimated on a sub-part of the dataset set apart at the start, often called a test set.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Alternatively, methods such as *k*-fold cross-validation are applied.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other strategies include using conformal prediction.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Regularization is a process of introducing additional information to solve an ill-posed problem or to prevent overfitting.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use various types of regularization.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because networks have so many parameters, they are prone to overfitting.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One method to reduce overfitting is dropout, introduced in 2014.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At each training stage, individual nodes are either "dropped out" of the net (ignored) with probability $1-p$ or kept with probability p , so that a reduced network is left; incoming and outgoing edges to a dropped-out node are also removed.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Only the reduced network is trained on the data in that stage.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The removed nodes are then reinserted into the network with their original weights.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the training stages, p is usually 0.5; for input nodes, it is typically much higher because information is directly lost when input nodes are ignored.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At testing time after training has finished, we would ideally like to find a sample average of all possible $2^{n}$ dropped-out networks; unfortunately this is unfeasible for large values of n .
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, we can find an approximation by using the full network with each node's output weighted by a factor of p , so the expected value of the output of any node is the same as in the training stages.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the biggest contribution of the dropout method: although it effectively generates $2^{n}$ neural nets, and as such allows for model combination, at test time only a single network needs to be tested.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By avoiding training all nodes on all training data, dropout decreases overfitting.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The method also significantly improves training speed.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This makes the model combination practical, even for deep neural networks.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The technique seems to reduce node interactions, leading them to learn more robust features that better generalize to new data.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is the generalization of dropout in which each connection, rather than each output unit, can be dropped with probability $1-p$ .
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each unit thus receives input from a random subset of units in the previous layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is similar to dropout as it introduces dynamic sparsity within the model, but differs in that the sparsity is on the weights, rather than the output vectors of a layer.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the fully connected layer with DropConnect becomes a sparsely connected layer in which the connections are chosen at random during the training stage.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A major drawback to dropout is that it does not have the same benefits for convolutional layers, where the neurons are not fully connected.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach is free of hyperparameters and can be combined with other regularization approaches, such as dropout and data augmentation.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] An alternate view of stochastic pooling is that it is equivalent to standard max pooling but with many copies of an input image, each having small local deformations.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to explicit elastic deformations of the input images, which delivers excellent performance on the MNIST data set.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using stochastic pooling in a multilayer model gives an exponential number of deformations since the selections in higher layers are independent of those below.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because the degree of model overfitting is determined by both its power and the amount of training it receives, providing a convolutional network with more training examples can reduce overfitting.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because there is often not enough available data to train, especially considering that some part should be spared for later testing, two approaches are to either generate new data from scratch (if possible) or perturb existing data to create new ones.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, input images can be cropped, rotated, or rescaled to create new examples with the same labels as the original training set.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One of the simplest methods to prevent overfitting of a network is to simply stop the training before overfitting has had a chance to occur.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It comes with the disadvantage that the learning process is halted.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another simple way to prevent overfitting is to limit the number of parameters, typically by limiting the number of hidden units in each layer or limiting network depth.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For convolutional networks, the filter size also affects the number of parameters.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Limiting the number of parameters restricts the predictive power of the network directly, reducing the complexity of the function that it can perform on the data, and thus limits the amount of overfitting.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A simple form of added regularizer is weight decay, which simply adds an additional error, proportional to the sum of weights (L1 norm) or squared magnitude (L2 norm) of the weight vector, to the error at each node.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The level of acceptable model complexity can be reduced by increasing the proportionality constant('alpha' hyperparameter), thus increasing the penalty for large weight vectors.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L2 regularization is the most common form of regularization.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It can be implemented by penalizing the squared magnitude of all parameters directly in the objective.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The L2 regularization has the intuitive interpretation of heavily penalizing peaky weight vectors and preferring diffuse weight vectors.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to multiplicative interactions between weights and inputs this has the useful property of encouraging the network to use all of its inputs a little rather than some of its inputs a lot.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It makes the weight vectors sparse during optimization.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, neurons with L1 regularization end up using only a sparse subset of their most important inputs and become nearly invariant to the noisy inputs.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L1 with L2 regularization can be combined; this is called elastic net regularization.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another form of regularization is to enforce an absolute upper bound on the magnitude of the weight vector for every neuron and use projected gradient descent to enforce the constraint.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In practice, this corresponds to performing the parameter update as normal, and then enforcing the constraint by clamping the weight vector ${\vec {w}}$ of every neuron to satisfy $\|{\vec {w}}\|_{2}<c$ .
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Some papers report improvements when using this form of regularization.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Pooling loses the precise spatial relationships between high-level parts (such as nose and mouth in a face image).
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] These relationships are needed for identity recognition.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Overlapping the pools so that each feature occurs in multiple pools, helps retain the information.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Translation alone cannot extrapolate the understanding of geometric relationships to a radically new viewpoint, such as a different orientation or scale.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] On the other hand, people are very good at extrapolating; after seeing a new shape once they can recognize it from a different viewpoint.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] An earlier common way to deal with this problem is to train the network on transformed data in different orientations, scales, lighting, etc. so that the network can cope with these variations.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is computationally intensive for large data-sets.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The alternative is to use a hierarchy of coordinate frames and use a group of neurons to represent a conjunction of the shape of the feature and its pose relative to the retina.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The pose relative to the retina is the relationship between the coordinate frame of the retina and the intrinsic features' coordinate frame.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Thus, one way to represent something is to embed the coordinate frame within it.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This allows large features to be recognized by using the consistency of the poses of their parts (e.g. nose and mouth poses make a consistent prediction of the pose of the whole face).
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This approach ensures that the higher-level entity (e.g. face) is present when the lower-level (e.g. nose and mouth) agree on its prediction of the pose.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The vectors of neuronal activity that represent pose ("pose vectors") allow spatial transformations modeled as linear operations that make it easier for the network to learn the hierarchy of visual entities and generalize across viewpoints.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is similar to the way the human visual system imposes coordinate frames in order to represent shapes.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs are often used in image recognition systems.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2012, an error rate of 0.23% on the MNIST database was reported.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper on using CNN for image classification reported that the learning process was "surprisingly fast"; in the same paper, the best published results as of 2011 were achieved in the MNIST database and the NORB database.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, a similar CNN called AlexNet won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] When applied to facial recognition, CNNs achieved a large decrease in error rate.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper reported a 97.6% recognition rate on "5,600 still images of more than 10 subjects".
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs were used to assess video quality in an objective way after manual training; the resulting system had a very low root mean square error.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and hundreds of object classes.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In the ILSVRC 2014, a large-scale visual recognition challenge, almost every highly ranked team used CNN as their basic framework.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The winner GoogLeNet (the foundation of DeepDream) increased the mean average precision of object detection to 0.439329, and reduced classification error to 0.06656, the best result to date.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its network applied more than 30 layers.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] That performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests was close to that of humans.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on a stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters, an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained categories such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, a many-layered CNN demonstrated the ability to spot faces from a wide range of angles, including upside down, even when partially occluded, with competitive performance.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The network was trained on a database of 200,000 images that included faces at various angles and orientations and a further 20 million images without faces.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They used batches of 128 images over 50,000 iterations.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to image data domains, there is relatively little work on applying CNNs to video classification.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Video is more complex than images since it has another (temporal) dimension.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, some extensions of CNNs into the video domain have been explored.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] One approach is to treat space and time as equivalent dimensions of the input and perform convolutions in both time and space.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another way is to fuse the features of two convolutional neural networks, one for the spatial and one for the temporal stream.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Long short-term memory (LSTM) recurrent units are typically incorporated after the CNN to account for inter-frame or inter-clip dependencies.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unsupervised learning schemes for training spatio-temporal features have been introduced, based on convolutional gated restricted Boltzmann machines and independent subspace analysis.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its application can be seen in text-to-video models.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have also been explored for natural language processing.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNN models are effective for various NLP problems and achieved excellent results in semantic parsing, search query retrieval, sentence modeling, classification, prediction and other traditional NLP tasks.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to traditional language processing methods such as recurrent neural networks, CNNs can represent different contextual realities of language that do not rely on a series-sequence assumption, while RNNs are better suitable when classical time series modeling is required.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been applied in ecological and behavioral research to automatically detect and quantify animal behavior from visual data, enabling identification of animals, tracking of individuals, estimation of pose, and classification of specific actions such as feeding, and social interactions.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Combined with multi-object tracking and temporal modeling, these systems can extract behavioral sequences over extended recordings, reducing reliance on manual annotation and increasing throughput for studies of individual variation, social networks, and collective dynamics.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A CNN with 1-D convolutions was used on time series in the frequency domain (spectral residual) by an unsupervised model to detect anomalies in the time domain.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Predicting the interaction between molecules and biological proteins can identify potential treatments.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, Atomwise introduced AtomNet, the first deep learning neural network for structure-based drug design.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The system trains directly on 3-dimensional representations of chemical interactions.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Similar to how image recognition networks learn to compose smaller, spatially proximate features into larger, complex structures, AtomNet discovers chemical features, such as aromaticity, sp3 carbons, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for multiple disease targets, most notably treatments for the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been used in the game of checkers.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] From 1999 to 2001, Fogel and Chellapilla published papers showing how a convolutional neural network could learn to play checkers using co-evolution.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The learning process did not use prior human professional games, but rather focused on a minimal set of information contained in the checkerboard: the location and type of pieces, and the difference in number of pieces between the two sides.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Ultimately, the program (Blondie24) was tested on 165 games against players and ranked in the highest 0.4%.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] It also earned a win against the program Chinook at its "expert" level of play.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In December 2014, Clark and Storkey published a paper showing that a CNN trained by supervised learning from a database of human professional games could outperform GNU Go and win some games against Monte Carlo tree search Fuego 1.1 in a fraction of the time it took Fuego to play.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Later it was announced that a large 12-layer convolutional neural network had correctly predicted the professional move in 55% of positions, equalling the accuracy of a 6 dan human player.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A couple of CNNs for choosing moves to try ("policy network") and evaluating positions ("value network") driving MCTS were used by AlphaGo, the first to beat the best human player at the time.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Recurrent neural networks are generally considered the best neural network architectures for time series forecasting (and sequence modeling in general), but recent studies show that convolutional networks can perform comparably or even better.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Dilated convolutions might enable one-dimensional convolutional neural networks to effectively learn time series dependences.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutions can be implemented more efficiently than RNN-based solutions, and they do not suffer from vanishing (or exploding) gradients.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional networks can provide an improved forecasting performance when there are multiple similar time series to learn from.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs can also be applied to further tasks in time series analysis (e.g., time series classification or quantile forecasting).
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] As archaeological findings such as clay tablets with cuneiform writing are increasingly acquired using 3D scanners, benchmark datasets are becoming available, including *HeiCuBeDa* providing almost 2000 normalized 2-D and 3-D datasets prepared with the GigaMesh Software Framework.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] So curvature-based measures are used in conjunction with geometric neural networks (GNNs), e.g. for period classification of those clay tablets being among the oldest documents of human history.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For many applications, training data is not very available.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional neural networks usually require a large amount of training data in order to avoid overfitting.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A common technique is to train the network on a larger data set from a related domain.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Once the network parameters have converged an additional training step is performed using the in-domain data to fine-tune the network weights, this is known as transfer learning.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Furthermore, this technique allows convolutional network architectures to successfully be applied to problems with tiny training sets.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] End-to-end training and prediction are common practice in computer vision.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, human interpretable explanations are required for critical systems such as self-driving cars.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] With recent advances in visual salience, spatial attention, and temporal attention, the most critical spatial regions/temporal instants could be visualized to justify the CNN predictions.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A deep Q-network (DQN) is a type of deep learning model that combines a deep neural network with Q-learning, a form of reinforcement learning.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unlike earlier reinforcement learning agents, DQNs that utilize CNNs can learn directly from high-dimensional sensory inputs via reinforcement learning.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Preliminary results were presented in 2014, with an accompanying paper in February 2015.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The research described an application to Atari 2600 gaming.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Other deep reinforcement learning models preceded it.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional deep belief networks (CDBN) have structure very similar to convolutional neural networks and are trained similarly to deep belief networks.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Therefore, they exploit the 2D structure of images, like CNNs do, and make use of pre-training like deep belief networks.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They provide a generic structure that can be used in many image and signal processing tasks.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Benchmark results on standard image datasets like CIFAR have been obtained using CDBNs.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The feed-forward architecture of convolutional neural networks was extended in the neural abstraction pyramid by lateral and feedback connections.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The resulting recurrent convolutional network allows for the flexible incorporation of contextual information to iteratively resolve local ambiguities.
[src:depth-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In contrast to previous models, image-like outputs at the highest resolution were generated, e.g., for semantic segmentation, image reconstruction, and object localization tasks.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-map] In 3D computer graphics and computer vision, a **depth map** is an image or image channel that contains information relating to the distance of the surfaces of scene objects from a viewpoint.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-map] The term is related (and may be analogous) to *depth buffer*, *Z-buffer*, *Z-buffering*, and *Z-depth*.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-map] The "Z" in these latter terms relates to a convention that the central axis of view of a camera is in the direction of the camera's Z axis, and not to the absolute Z axis of a scene.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-map] Two different depth maps can be seen here, together with the original model from which they are derived.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-map] The first depth map shows luminance in proportion to the distance from the camera.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-map] Nearer surfaces are darker; further surfaces are lighter.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-map] The second depth map shows luminance in relation to the distances from a nominal focal plane.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-map] Surfaces closer to the focal plane are darker; surfaces further from the focal plane are lighter, (both closer to and also further away from the viewpoint).
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Depth perception arises from a variety of depth cues.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] These are typically classified into binocular cues and monocular cues.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Binocular cues are based on the receipt of sensory information in three dimensions by both eyes while monocular cues can be observed with just one eye.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Binocular cues include retinal disparity, which exploits parallax and vergence.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Stereopsis is made possible with binocular vision.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Monocular cues include relative size (distant objects subtend smaller visual angles than near objects), texture gradient, occlusion, linear perspective, contrast differences, and motion parallax.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Monocular cues provide depth information even when viewing a scene with only one eye.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] When an observer moves, the apparent relative motion of several stationary objects against a background gives hints about their relative distance.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] If information about the direction and velocity of movement is known, motion parallax can provide absolute depth information.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] This effect can be seen clearly when riding in a car.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Nearby things pass quickly, while far-off objects appear stationary.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] When an object moves toward the observer, the retinal projection of an object expands over a period of time, which leads to the perception of movement in a line toward the observer.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Another name for this phenomenon is *depth from optical expansion*.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The dynamic stimulus change enables the observer not only to see the object as moving, but to perceive the distance of the moving object.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Thus, in this context, the changing size serves as a distance cue.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] A related phenomenon is the visual system's capacity to calculate time-to-contact (TTC) of an approaching object from the rate of optical expansion – a useful ability in contexts ranging from driving a car to playing a ball game.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] However, the calculation of TTC is, strictly speaking, a perception of velocity rather than depth.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] If a stationary rigid figure (for example, a wire cube) is placed in front of a point source of light so that its shadow falls on a translucent screen, an observer on the other side of the screen will see a two-dimensional pattern of lines.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] But if the cube rotates, the visual system will extract the necessary information for perception of the third dimension from the movements of the lines, and a cube is seen.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] This is an example of the *kinetic depth effect*.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The effect also occurs when the rotating object is solid (rather than an outline figure), provided that the projected shadow consists of lines which have definite corners or end points, and that these lines change in both length and orientation during the rotation.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The property of parallel lines converging in the distance, at infinity, allows us to reconstruct the relative distance of two parts of an object, or of landscape features.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] An example would be standing on a straight road, looking down the road, and noticing the road narrows as it goes off in the distance.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Visual perception of perspective in real space, for instance in rooms, in settlements and in nature, is a result of several optical impressions and the interpretation by the visual system.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The angle of vision is important for the apparent size.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] A nearby object is imaged on a larger area on the retina, while the same object or an object of the same size further away is imaged on a smaller area.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The perception of perspective is possible when looking with one eye only, but stereoscopic vision enhances the impression of the spatial.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Regardless of whether the light rays entering the eye come from a three-dimensional space or from a two-dimensional image, they hit the inside of the eye on the retina as a surface.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] What a person sees, is based on the reconstruction by their visual system, in which one and the same image on the retina can be interpreted both two-dimensionally and three-dimensionally.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] If a three-dimensional interpretation has been recognised, it receives a preference and determines the perception.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] In spatial vision, the horizontal line of sight can play a role.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] In the picture taken from the window of a house, the horizontal line of sight is at the level of the second floor (yellow line).
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Below this line, the further away objects are, the higher up in the visual field they appear.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Above the horizontal line of sight, objects that are further away appear lower than those that are closer.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] To represent spatial impressions in graphical perspective, one can use a vanishing point.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] When looking at long geographical distances, perspective effects also partially result from the angle of vision, but not only by this.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] In picture 5 of the series, in the background is Mont Blanc, the highest mountain in the Alps.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] It appears lower than the mountain in front in the center of the picture.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Measurements and calculations can be used to determine the proportion of the curvature of Earth in the subjectively perceived proportions.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] If two objects are known to be the same size (for example, two trees) but their absolute size is unknown, relative size cues can provide information about the relative depth of the two objects.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] If one subtends a larger visual angle on the retina than the other, the object which subtends the larger visual angle appears closer.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Since the visual angle of an object projected onto the retina decreases with distance, this information can be combined with previous knowledge of the object's size to determine the absolute depth of the object.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] For example, people are generally familiar with the size of an average automobile.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] This prior knowledge can be combined with information about the angle it subtends on the retina to determine the absolute depth of an automobile in a scene.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Even if the actual size of the object is unknown and there is only one object visible, a smaller object seems farther away than a large object that is presented at the same location.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Due to light scattering by the atmosphere, objects that are a great distance away have lower luminance contrast and lower color saturation.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Due to this, images seem hazy the farther they are away from a person's point of view.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] In computer graphics, this is often called "distance fog".
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The foreground has high contrast; the background has low contrast.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Objects differing only in their contrast with a background appear to be at different depths.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The color of distant objects is also shifted toward the blue end of the spectrum (for example, distant mountains).
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Some painters, notably Cézanne, employ "warm" pigments (red, yellow and orange) to bring features forward towards the viewer, and "cool" ones (blue, violet, and blue-green) to indicate the part of a form that curves away from the picture plane.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Accommodation is an oculomotor cue for depth perception.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] When humans try to focus on distant objects, the ciliary muscles relax, allowing the eye lens to become thinner, which increases the focal length.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Depth perception of distant objects is made possible by other methods besides accommodation.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The kinesthetic sensations of the contracting and relaxing ciliary muscles (intraocular muscles) are sent to the visual cortex where they are used for interpreting distance and depth.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Accommodation is only effective for distances less than 2 meters.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Occultation (also referred to as *interposition*) happens when near surfaces overlap far surfaces.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] If one object partially blocks the view of another object, humans perceive it as closer.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] However, this information only allows the observer to make a "ranking" of relative nearness.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The presence of monocular ambient occlusions consist of the object's texture and geometry.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] These phenomena are able to reduce depth perception latency both in natural and artificial stimuli.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] At the outer extremes of the visual field, parallel lines become curved, as in a photo taken through a fisheye lens.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] This effect, although it is usually eliminated from both art and photos by the cropping or framing of a picture, greatly enhances the viewer's sense of being positioned within a real, three-dimensional space.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Fine details on nearby objects can be seen clearly, whereas such details are not visible on faraway objects.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Texture gradients are the grains of an item.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] For example, on a long gravel road, the gravel near the observer can be clearly seen of shape, size and colour.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] In the distance, the road's texture cannot be clearly differentiated.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The way that light falls on an object and reflects off its surfaces, and the shadows that are cast by objects provide an effective cue for the brain to determine the shape of objects and their position in space.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Selective image blurring is very commonly used in photography and video to establish the impression of depth.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] This can act as a monocular cue even when all other cues are removed.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] It may contribute to depth perception in natural retinal images, because the depth of focus of the human eye is limited.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] In addition, there are several depth estimation algorithms based on defocus and blurring.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Some jumping spiders are known to use image defocus to judge depth.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] When an object is visible relative to the horizon, humans tend to perceive objects which are closer to the horizon as being farther away from them, and objects which are farther from the horizon as being closer to them.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] In addition, if an object moves from a position close to the horizon to a position higher or lower than the horizon, it will appear to move closer to the viewer.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Ocular parallax is a perceptual effect where the rotation of the eye causes perspective-dependent image shifts.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] This happens because the optical center and the rotation center of the eye are not the same.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Ocular parallax does not require head movement.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] It is separate and distinct from motion parallax.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Binocular cues provide depth information when viewing a scene with both eyes.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Animals that have their eyes placed frontally can also use information derived from the different projections of objects onto each retina to judge depth.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] By using two images of the same scene obtained from slightly different angles, it is possible to triangulate the distance to an object with a high degree of accuracy.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Each eye views a slightly different angle of an object seen by the left and right eyes.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] This happens because of the horizontal separation parallax of the eyes.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] If an object is far away, the disparity of that image falling on both retinas will be small.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] If the object is close or near, the disparity will be large.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] It is stereopsis that tricks people into thinking they perceive depth when viewing Magic Eyes, autostereograms, 3D movies, and stereoscopic photos.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Convergence is a binocular oculomotor cue for distance and depth perception.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Because of stereopsis, the two eyeballs focus on the same object; in doing so they converge.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The convergence will stretch the extraocular muscles – the receptors for this are muscle spindles.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] As happens with the monocular accommodation cue, kinesthetic sensations from these extraocular muscles also help in distance and depth perception.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The angle of convergence is smaller when the eye is fixating on objects which are far away.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Convergence is effective for distances less than 10 meters.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Antonio Medina Puerta demonstrated that retinal images with no parallax disparity but with different shadows were fused stereoscopically, imparting depth perception to the imaged scene.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] He named the phenomenon "shadow stereopsis".
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Shadows are therefore an important, stereoscopic cue for depth perception.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Of these various cues, only convergence, accommodation and familiar size provide absolute distance information.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] All other cues are relative (as in, they can only be used to tell which objects are closer relative to others).
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Isaac Newton proposed that the optic nerve of humans and other primates has a specific architecture on its way from the eye to the brain.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Nearly half of the fibres from the human retina project to the brain hemisphere on the same side as the eye from which they originate.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] That architecture is labelled hemi-decussation or ipsilateral (same sided) visual projections (IVP).
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] In most other animals, these nerve fibres cross to the opposite side of the brain.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Bernhard von Gudden showed that the OC contains both crossed and uncrossed retinal fibers, and Ramon y Cajal observed that the grade of hemidecussation differs between species.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Gordon Lynn Walls formalized a commonly accepted notion into the law of Newton–Müller–Gudden (NGM) saying: that the degree of optic fibre decussation in the optic chiasm is contrariwise related to the degree of frontal orientation of the optical axes of the eyes.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] In other words, that the number of fibers that do not cross the midline is proportional to the size of the binocular visual field.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] However, an issue of the Newton–Müller–Gudden law is the considerable interspecific variation in IVP seen in non-mammalian species.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] That variation is unrelated to mode of life, taxonomic situation, and the overlap of visual fields.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The eye-forelimb (EF) hypothesis suggests that the need for accurate eye-hand control was key in the evolution of stereopsis.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The EF hypothesis postulates that it has a selective value to have short neural pathways between areas of the brain that receive visual information about the hand and the motor nuclei that control the coordination of the hand.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The essence of the EF hypothesis is that evolutionary transformation in OC will affect the length and thereby speed of these neural pathways.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The reverse is true for the left hand, the processing of visual, tactile information, and motor command – all of which takes place in the right hemisphere.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Cats and arboreal (tree-climbing) marsupials have analogous arrangements (between 30 and 45% of IVP and forward-directed eyes).
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The result will be that visual info of their forelimbs reaches the proper (executing) hemisphere.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The evolution has resulted in small, and gradual fluctuations in the direction of the nerve pathways in the OC.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] This transformation can go in either direction.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Snakes, cyclostomes and other animals that lack extremities have relatively many IVP.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Notably these animals have no limbs (hands, paws, fins or wings) to direct.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Besides, the left and right body parts of snakelike animals cannot move independently of each other.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] For example, if a snake coils clockwise, its left eye only sees the left body-part and in an anticlockwise position the same eye will see just the right body-part.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] For that reason, it is functional for snakes to have some IVP in the OC (Naked).
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Cyclostome descendants (in other words, most vertebrates) that due to evolution ceased to curl and, instead developed forelimbs would be favored by achieving completely crossed pathways as long as forelimbs were primarily occupied in a lateral direction.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Reptiles such as snakes that lost their limbs, would gain by recollecting a cluster of uncrossed fibres in their evolution.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] That seems to have happened, providing further support for the EF hypothesis.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Mice' paws are usually busy only in the lateral visual fields.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] So, it is in accordance with the EF hypothesis that mice have laterally situated eyes and very few crossings in the OC.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The list from the animal kingdom supporting the EF hypothesis is long (BBE).
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The EF hypothesis applies to essentially all vertebrates while the NGM law and stereopsis hypothesis largely apply just to mammals.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Even some mammals display important exceptions, e.g. dolphins have only uncrossed pathways although they are predators.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] It is a common suggestion that predatory animals generally have frontally-placed eyes since that permit them to evaluate the distance to prey, whereas preyed-upon animals have eyes in a lateral position, since that permit them to scan and detect the enemy in time.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] However, many predatory animals may also become prey, and several predators, for instance, the crocodile, have laterally situated eyes and no IVP at all.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] That OC architecture will provide short nerve connections and optimal eye control of the crocodile's front foot.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Birds, usually have laterally situated eyes, in spite of that they manage to fly through e.g. a dense wood.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Most open-plain herbivores, especially hoofed grazers, lack binocular vision because they have their eyes on the sides of the head, providing a panoramic, almost 360°, view of the horizon – enabling them to notice the approach of predators from almost any direction.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] However, most predators have both eyes looking forwards, allowing binocular depth perception and helping them to judge distances when they pounce or swoop down onto their prey.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Animals that spend a lot of time in trees take advantage of binocular vision in order to accurately judge distances when rapidly moving from branch to branch.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Matt Cartmill, a physical anthropologist and anatomist at Boston University, has criticized this theory, citing other arboreal species which lack binocular vision, such as squirrels and certain birds.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Instead, he proposes a "Visual Predation Hypothesis," which argues that ancestral primates were insectivorous predators resembling tarsiers, subject to the same selection pressure for frontal vision as other predatory species.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] He also uses this hypothesis to account for the specialization of primate hands, which he suggests became adapted for grasping prey, somewhat like the way raptors employ their talons.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Photographs capturing perspective are two-dimensional images that often illustrate the illusion of depth.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Photography utilizes size, environmental context, lighting, textural gradient, and other effects to capture the illusion of depth.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Stereoscopes and Viewmasters, as well as 3D films, employ binocular vision by forcing the viewer to see two images created from slightly different positions (points of view).
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Charles Wheatstone was the first to discuss depth perception being a cue of binocular disparity.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] He invented the stereoscope, which is an instrument with two eyepieces that displays two photographs of the same location/scene taken at relatively different angles.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] When observed, separately by each eye, the pairs of images induced a clear sense of depth.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] By contrast, a telephoto lens—used in televised sports, for example, to zero in on members of a stadium audience—has the opposite effect.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The viewer sees the size and detail of the scene as if it were close enough to touch, but the camera's perspective is still derived from its actual position a hundred meters away, so background faces and objects appear about the same size as those in the foreground.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Trained artists are keenly aware of the various methods for indicating spatial depth (color shading, distance fog, perspective and relative size), and take advantage of them to make their works appear "real".
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The viewer feels it would be possible to reach in and grab the nose of a Rembrandt portrait or an apple in a Cézanne still life—or step inside a landscape and walk around among its trees and rocks.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Cubism was based on the idea of incorporating multiple points of view in a painted image, as if to simulate the visual experience of being physically in the presence of the subject, and seeing it from different angles.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The radical experiments of Georges Braque, Pablo Picasso, Jean Metzinger's *Nu à la cheminée*, Albert Gleizes's *La Femme aux Phlox*, or Robert Delaunay's views of the Eiffel Tower, employ the explosive angularity of Cubism to exaggerate the traditional illusion of three-dimensional space.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] The subtle use of multiple points of view can be found in the pioneering late work of Cézanne, which both anticipated and inspired the first actual Cubists.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Cézanne's landscapes and still lives powerfully suggest the artist's own highly developed depth perception.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] Cubism, and indeed most of modern art is an attempt to confront, if not resolve, the paradox of suggesting spatial depth on a flat surface, and explore that inherent contradiction through innovative ways of seeing, as well as new methods of drawing and painting.
[src:depth-estimation/depth-perception] In robotics and computer vision, depth perception is often achieved using sensors such as RGBD cameras.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] In the science of visual perception, **stereopsis** is the sensation that objects in space extend into depth, and that objects have different distances from each other.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] This sensation is much stronger than the suggestion of depth that is created by two-dimensional perspective.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] In humans, at least two mechanisms produce the sensation of stereopsis: binocular depth vision and (monocular) motion vision.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] In binocular depth vision, the sensation arises from processing differences in retinal images resulting from the two eyes looking from different, but similar, directions (binocular disparity).
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] In motion vision, the sensation arises from processing motion information when the observer moves (e.g. optical flow, parallax).
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The sensation of stereopsis is similar in both cases.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] In research on depth vision, the term *stereopsis* is primarily used for binocular depth vision and not for the sensation of depth resulting from motion vision.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Sometimes the term "relative depth" is used.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] This term emphasizes that it refers not to the distance to the observer, but to the mutual depth relationships of the perceived objects.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] If the meaning is clear from the context, the single word "depth" is also used instead of "relative depth." The word *stereopsis* comes from Greek *stereós* 'solid' and *ópsis* 'appearance, sight'.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Together, these indicate seeing the outside of three-dimensional, "solid" objects.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Binocular depth vision comes in two qualities: *coarse stereopsis* and *fine stereopsis*.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Fine stereopsis plays a role in the recognition of shapes and objects, and coarse stereopsis in spatial localization.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Research into binocular depth vision begins with Charles Wheatstone, who was the first to make a stereoscope.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] At the end of the 19th century, he was the first to demonstrate that horizontal disparity of vertical lines is sufficient to evoke a sensation of depth.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Bela Julesz showed in the 20th century that the sensation also occurs with dots (random dot stereogram) and that depth vision precedes the perception of forms.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Jodi Krol showed around the same time that a light transition (edge) is necessary, but that two corresponding edges of opposite contrast do not give a depth sensation.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] He also found that the depth of the surfaces between these edges is an interpretation.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The left and right visual directions should be stimulated at approximately the same time, but this does not have to happen at exactly the same time.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] This is illustrated by the Puflrich illusion.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Kenneth Ogle (1950) found that the quality of depth perception differs for small and large disparities and on this basis distinguishes different types of stereopsis.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] It is generally accepted that in the absence of a sensation of stereopsis the perceived image is usually seen in the plane of the horopter.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] John Foley (1972) describes that in exceptional cases the image can also appear slightly behind or in front of the horopter.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Jodi Krol (1982) shows that the latter happens when the eyes are unconsciously directed slightly in front of or behind the intended fixation point due to certain reflexes and the fixation point is therefore not on the horopter.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Finally, nerve cells have been found in the visual cortex that are tuned to a certain disparity.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] These cells form the basis for neural models for binocular depth vision and for the solution of the correspondence problem to be discussed.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] These cells are part of two neurophysiological mechanisms that are specialized in shape and object recognition and in spatial localization, respectively.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] When attention is directed to a point F in space, automatic eye movements are performed, causing the eye to rotate and point F is mapped onto the point of the eye with which it can see most sharply, the fovea.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The direction in which the eye then looks is called the *principle ocular direction*.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Every other point in space is seen by the eye in a certain direction that can be expressed as the angle that this direction makes with the principle direction.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] This is called *visual direction* or simply *direction*.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The directions in which each eye sees the same object are sometimes the same, but usually not.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The difference in directions is called **disparity**.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The separate article on directional vision explains how the brain combines the directions that each eye sees into a combined image with single images, double images and fused images that are apparently seen from a point in the middle between both eyes (cyclopean eye).
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The horizontal distance of approximately 6.5 cm between the two eyes ensures that points in space that are at different depths relative to the fixation point have a horizontal difference in direction.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] This difference is called **horizontal disparity** and is expressed as the difference between the angles α and β in the figure.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] In addition to horizontal disparity, there is also *vertical disparity.* This term indicates a vertical disalignment between the two eyes which can be caused by vertical eye movement or tilting the head.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The latter is usually partially or completely corrected with automatically performed eye movements.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Vertical disparities can also evoke a sense of depth in some cases.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The terms horizontal and vertical disparity only make sense when the observer is upright.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Under neurophysiological mechanisms it can be read that motion parallax is possibly processed in the same system as coarse stereopsis.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Points at the same depth as the fixation point lie on a circle through both eyes and the fixation point.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Points on this circle project onto corresponding points in both eyes, i.e. onto points that look in the same direction in the left and right eye.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] We perceive the horopter as a kind of screen on which we see the world.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The directions in both eyes of a point C that is closer than the horopter are seen crossed on this screen: the direction in which the direction of the left eye is seen is to the right of the direction of the right eye.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] This is called crossed disparity or negative disparity.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The directions in both eyes of a point P that is further away than the horopter are seen side by side on this screen: the right direction is seen on the right.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] This is called parallel disparity or positive disparity.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Charles Wheatstone showed in 1838 that two objects that differ only in horizontal disparity produce a sensation of relative depth.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] To ensure that this sensation could not be caused by two-dimensional perspective, he used a pair of flat plates with two vertical lines, a line stereogram, to represent the visual directions, and invented the stereoscope to view these plates.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Ogle (1950) investigated how the sensation of depth depends on the degree of disparity.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Ogle asked an observer to fixate a point F and then moved a vertical rod Y in depth away from X.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The magnitude of the perceived depth was found to increase linearly at small disparities, and to decrease again at larger disparities, and to be completely absent at even larger disparities.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] In the latter case, Y was seen at the distance of the horopter.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] If Ogle asked the observer to look back and forth between X and Y (vergence), depth perception was found to be possible over a much larger range.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] According to the research of Ogle and others, depth differences are perceived only in a narrow region of space, further away and closer than the horopter and this occurs with three qualities: *fine stereopsis*, *coarse stereopsis* and *no stereopsis*.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] With **fine stereopsis** the observer can indicate the size of the depth: the greater the disparity, the greater the perceived depth.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Ogle used the term *patent stereopsis* for this.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Later researchers replaced this term with *fine stereopsis*.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] With **coarse stereopsis** the observer can indicate whether one object is further away than the other, but not how much.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Ogle used the term *qualitative stereopsis* for this.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Later researchers replaced this term with *coarse stereopsis*.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] In the remaining area, objects are seen without depth sensation, at or around the distance of the horopter, and usually as a double image.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Horizontal disparity is a condition for seeing relative depth, but not a sufficient condition.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The visual directions in the left and right eyes must also have a certain similarity, such as equal light transitions (edges) or spots, and must be stimulated more or less simultaneously.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Eye movements ensure that objects in space fall on corresponding points in both eyes as much as possible and the disparity remains as small as possible.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Hering suggested as early as 1864 that the visual directions must contain equal "edges" and that the surfaces between these edges are "filled in" during perception.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] This has been confirmed by Krol (1982, p.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Edges with an opposite contrast do not give a depth sensation.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Seeing an opposite contrast triggers an eye movement reflex, which means that the opposite contrasts do not fall on corresponding points and the edges appear to lie slightly in front of or behind the fixation point.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The color and brightness do not have to be the same.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Stereopsis even occurs with opposite colors, where the perceived color alternates between the two colors.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Julesz (1971) has shown with random dot stereograms that stereopsis also occurs when the visual directions consist of small, random white and black spots, where a certain group of spots in the left image has shifted in the right eye.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Each eye alone sees only spots, but both eyes together see the group of shifted spots as a shape with depth.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The visual direction in the left and right eyes must be stimulated simultaneously or in quick succession.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] An illustration of non-simultaneous stimulation is the Pulfrich illusion, in which (according to the explanation of the Pulfrich effect) a dark glass in front of one of the eyes delays the signals from that eye.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] When viewing the back and forth movement of a car windshield wiper with a gray filter or sunglasses lens in front of one eye, the wiper appears to make an elliptical movement in depth.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] It even appears to move through the glass.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] This illusion was first described by Pulfrich in 1922.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Eye movements are important to achieve and maintain the conditions necessary for stereopsis.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Vertical eye movements and rotational movements ensure that the images in the left and right eyes are at the correct, equal height and remain at the same height when the head is not upright.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Vergence movements (convergence and divergence) ensure that the horopter is positioned and held in space in such a way that objects of interest lie optimally within the area for stereopsis.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] A large part of these movements occurs reflexively.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] To ensure that the eyes fixate the correct point (vergence) and that reflexes do not influence the result during research, various methods are used.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] One method consists of unexpectedly and briefly presenting the stimuli so that the eyes do not have time to perform an eye movement reflex.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Another method consists of making visible with so-called vernier lines that the observer is fixating correctly.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The left and right eyes both see a hairline, above and below the fixation point respectively, that the other eye does not see and that must be aligned.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] A final method consists of registering the eye movements during the experiment.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] If there is a visual direction in one eye that can be combined with multiple visual directions in the other eye to give a sensation of depth, then the brain is faced with a choice problem: which combination is the right one and is seen?
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Julesz calls this the correspondence problem and has investigated this problem with random dot stereograms.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] This research shows, among other things, that the visual system prefers to see surfaces (globality principle) and that shapes are only filled in after disparities have been established.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Krol has also investigated the correspondence problem, but now with natural stimuli (double-nail illusion), whereby by feeling and looking from multiple positions it can be determined which "interpretation" is the correct one.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] It turns out that the interpretation with the least depth is always seen.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] In the double-nail illusion, two nails or needles are placed at the shown positions A and B.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Under the right observation conditions, these needles are invisible and instead of these real objects, two needles are seen at positions C and D.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] These needles are not really there and are therefore called ghost images by Krol.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] In the 1960s, Horace Barlow, Colin Blakemore, and Jack Pettigrew found neurons in the cat visual cortex that had their receptive fields in different horizontal positions in the two eyes.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] This established the neural basis for stereopsis.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Their findings were disputed by David Hubel and Torsten Wiesel, although they eventually conceded when they found similar neurons in the monkey visual cortex.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] In the 1980s, Gian Poggio and others found neurons in V2 of the monkey brain that responded to the depth of random-dot stereograms.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Fine stereopsis appears to be processed by a system of small cells that processes fine detail and color in an environment that changes relatively slowly.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] This system plays a major role in the recognition of shapes and objects and is concerned with "what" is seen.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Coarse stereopsis (and associated double vision) is processed by a system of large cells that process large changes such as motion, contrast, and rapid changes in a relatively rapidly changing environment.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] This system is focused on localization and orientation in space.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The nerve pathways of both systems run from the eyes to the visual cortex.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The fine stereopsis system then extends to the inferior temporal cortex where "what" information is processed (parvo pathway).
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] The coarse stereopsis system extends to the posterior parietal cortex where "where" and "how" information is processed (magno pathway).
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Both systems appear to operate partially in parallel but also work together.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] If one system fails, the other system can sometimes still function: people who do not have fine stereopsis can sometimes experience coarse stereopsis.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Stereopsis has a positive effect on practicing practical tasks such as threading a needle and catching balls (especially in fast ball games).), pouring liquids, and others.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Occupational activities may include operating stereoscopic instruments such as a binocular microscope.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Although some of these tasks may benefit from compensation of the visual system by means of other depth cues, there are some functions for which stereopsis is necessary.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Regarding driving, one study found a positive effect of stereopsis in specific situations, only at intermediate distances.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Furthermore, a study among elderly people found that glare, visual field loss and the useful visual field were predictors of crash involvement, whereas older adults' visual acuity, contrast sensitivity, and stereoacuity scores were not associated with crashes.
[src:depth-estimation/stereopsis] Stereopsis is also important for object recognition and for seeing through camouflage.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] Humans perceive a great deal of information about the three-dimensional structure in their environment by moving around it.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] When the observer moves, objects around them move different amounts depending on their distance from the observer.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] This is known as motion parallax, and this depth information can be used to generate an accurate 3D representation of the world around them.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] Finding structure from motion presents a similar problem to finding structure from stereo vision.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] In both instances, the correspondence between images and the reconstruction of 3D object needs to be found.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] To find correspondence between images, features such as corner points (edges with gradients in multiple directions) are tracked from one image to the next.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] One of the most widely used feature detectors is the scale-invariant feature transform (SIFT).
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] It uses the maxima from a difference-of-Gaussians (DOG) pyramid as features.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] The first step in SIFT is finding a dominant gradient direction.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] To make it rotation-invariant, the descriptor is rotated to fit this orientation.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] Another common feature detector is the SURF (*speeded-up robust features*).
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] In SURF, the DOG is replaced with a Hessian matrix-based blob detector.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] Also, instead of evaluating the gradient histograms, SURF computes for the sums of gradient components and the sums of their absolute values.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] Its usage of integral images allows the features to be detected extremely quickly with high detection rate.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] Therefore, comparing to SIFT, SURF is a faster feature detector with drawback of less accuracy in feature positions.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] Another type of feature recently made practical for structure from motion are general curves (e.g., locally an edge with gradients in one direction), part of a technology known as *pointless SfM*, useful when point features are insufficient, common in man-made environments.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] The features detected from all the images will then be matched.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] One of the matching algorithms that track features from one image to another is the Lucas–Kanade tracker.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] Sometimes some of the matched features are incorrectly matched.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] This is why the matches should also be filtered.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] RANSAC (random sample consensus) is the algorithm that is usually used to remove the outlier correspondences.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] In the paper of Fischler and Bolles, RANSAC is used to solve the *location determination problem* (LDP), where the objective is to determine the points in space that project onto an image into a set of landmarks with known locations.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] The feature trajectories over time are then used to reconstruct their 3D positions and the camera's motion.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] An alternative is given by so-called direct approaches, where geometric information (3D structure and camera motion) is directly estimated from the images, without intermediate abstraction to features or corners.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] There are several approaches to structure from motion.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] In incremental SfM, camera poses are solved for and added one by one to the collection.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] In global SfM, the poses of all cameras are solved for at the same time.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] A somewhat intermediate approach is out-of-core SfM, where several partial reconstructions are computed that are then integrated into a global solution.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] Structure-from-motion photogrammetry with multi-view stereo provides hyperscale landform models using images acquired from a range of digital cameras and optionally a network of ground control points.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] The technique is not limited in temporal frequency and can provide point cloud data comparable in density and accuracy to those generated by terrestrial and airborne laser scanning at a fraction of the cost.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] Structure from motion is also useful in remote or rugged environments where terrestrial laser scanning is limited by equipment portability and airborne laser scanning is limited by terrain roughness causing loss of data and image foreshortening.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] The technique has been applied in many settings such as rivers, badlands, sandy coastlines, fault zones, landslides, and coral reef settings.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] A full range of digital cameras can be utilized, including digital SLR's, compact digital cameras and even smart phones.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] Generally though, higher accuracy data will be achieved with more expensive cameras, which include lenses of higher optical quality.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] The technique therefore offers exciting opportunities to characterize surface topography in unprecedented detail and, with multi-temporal data, to detect elevation, position and volumetric changes that are symptomatic of earth surface processes.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] Structure from motion can be placed in the context of other digital surveying methods.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] Cultural heritage is present everywhere.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] Its structural control, documentation and conservation is one of humanity's main duties (UNESCO).
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] Under this point of view, SfM is used in order to properly estimate situations as well as planning and maintenance efforts and costs, control and restoration.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] The use is accurate as only qualitative considerations are needed.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] It is fast enough to respond to the monument's immediate management needs.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] The first operational phase is an accurate preparation of the photogrammetric surveying where is established the relation between best distance from the object, focal length, the ground sampling distance (GSD) and the sensor's resolution.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] With this information the programmed photographic acquisitions must be made using vertical overlapping of at least 60%.
[src:depth-estimation/structure-from-motion] Furthermore, structure-from-motion photogrammetry represents a non-invasive, highly flexible and low-cost methodology to digitalize historical documents.
